\cf0 The Chow Chow has been identified as a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dog_breed#Basal_breeds"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 basal breed}} that predates the emergence of the modern breeds in the 19th Century.
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3  
\fs24 \cf0 \nosupersub \ulnone One writer proposed that the Chow Chow originated in China 2,000 years ago or possibly originated in Arctic Asia 3,000 years ago which migrated to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mongolia"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul Mongolia}}, then to China.\
One Chinese legend mentions large war dogs from Central Asia that resembled black-tongued lions. One Chinese ruler was said to own 5,000 Chows. The Chinese also used Chows to pull {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dog_sled"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul dog sleds}} through swampy terrain, and this was remarked upon by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marco_Polo"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul Marco Polo}}.\
Today, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Kennel_Club"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul American Kennel Club}} registers approximately 10,000 Chow Chows a year. The {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_Kennel_Club"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul Canadian Kennel Club}} registers approximately 350.\
The Chow Chow is a sturdily built dog, square in profile, with a broad skull and small, triangular, erect ears with rounded tips. The breed is known for a very dense {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double_coat"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul double coat}} that is either smooth or rough.
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul  
\fs24 \cf0 \nosupersub \ulnone The fur is particularly thick in the neck area, giving it a distinctive {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruff_(clothing)"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul ruff}} or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/mane"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul mane}} appearance. The coat may be shaded/self-red, black, blue, cinnamon/fawn, or cream.
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul  
\fs24 \cf0 \nosupersub \ulnone Not all these color varieties are recognized as valid in all countries. Individuals with patchy or multicolored coats are considered to be outside the breed standard. Chow Chow eyes are typically deep set and almond shaped. The breed is unique by their purple/blue-black tongue which no other breed has except {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shar_Pei"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul Shar Pei}}, and has very straight hind legs, resulting in a rather stilted gait.
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul  
